value: Melon-shaped ewer and cover with lotus design. Stoneware, thrown, with parts attached, indented, incised and celadon-glazed. The body is twelve-lobed, has a well-formed spout, a handle with a double loop, and a flower-shaped cover, also with a loop. It has a shallow footring.  The ewer is incised around the rim and the base with bands of double lotus petals, and each of the twelve lobes is decorated with a precisely engraved lotus spray. The lid is incised with a scroll motif on each lobe. The glaze has a clear, pale green celadon tone, with a fine crackle evenly covering the whole surface.  The footring, from which the glaze had been wiped before firing, shows four large fire-clay spur-marks.
